The USAAF [B-25B Mitchell](/North_American_B-25_Mitchell), a medium bomber.
Polish [PZL.37 Łoś](/PZL.37_%C5%81o%C5%9B), a medium bomber.
The Japanese [Mitsubishi G4M](/Mitsubishi_G4M) "Betty", a medium bomber.

A medium bomber, a term now largely relegated to the dusty archives of military aviation history, once designated a specific class of [military](/Military) [bomber](/Bomber) [aircraft](/Fixed-wing_aircraft). These machines were meticulously engineered to deliver medium-sized [bombloads](/Aerial_bomb) across medium [range](/Range_(aeronautics)) distances. The very nomenclature served a pragmatic purpose, differentiating them from their more diminutive counterparts, the [light bombers](/Light_bomber), and the substantially larger, more formidable [heavy bombers](/Heavy_bomber). In the era of their prominence, these "mediums" typically boasted a payload capacity of approximately two tons of ordnance, a stark contrast to the single ton carried by light bombers or the impressive four tons (or often, significantly more) that their heavy bomber brethren could lift into the unforgiving skies.

This rather precise, if ultimately transient, categorization was most actively employed in the tense years leading up to and throughout [World War II](/World_War_II). It was a product of the technological constraints and possibilities of the time, dictated by the prevailing advancements in [aircraft engine](/Aircraft_engine) design and the nascent field of [aeronautical technology](/Aerospace_engineering). These parameters, ever-evolving, shaped the very form and function of bomber aircraft. However, as is the cyclical nature of human ingenuity, the post-war landscape saw a rapid and decisive shift. Medium bombers, much like the term itself, found themselves swiftly superseded in the world's burgeoning [air forces](/Air_force) by a new generation of aircraft, which were invariably more advanced, more versatile, and simply more capable. The era of the medium bomber, as a distinct class, was remarkably brief, a fleeting moment in the relentless pursuit of aerial dominance.

## History

In the nascent years of the 1930s, a global impetus for military modernization swept through numerous [air forces](/Air_force). Many nations found their existing [bomber](/Bomber) [aircraft](/Fixed-wing_aircraft) fleets, often relics of an earlier age, composed predominantly of older, less capable [biplanes](/Biplane). The urgent demand was for something faster, more robust, and significantly more survivable. The ensuing wave of new designs typically manifested as twin-engined [monoplanes](/Monoplane), a dramatic leap forward in aerodynamic efficiency. These aircraft frequently featured all-metal construction, a significant improvement over the fabric-covered frames of their predecessors, offering enhanced durability and structural integrity. They were meticulously optimized for a performance envelope that prioritized both speed and altitude, aiming to provide a crucial edge in evading the rapidly evolving designs of contemporary [fighter aircraft](/Fighter_aircraft). This period was, after all, an arms race in the purest sense, with offensive and defensive capabilities locked in a constant, brutal dance of innovation.

Interestingly, and perhaps a testament to the pragmatic, if somewhat constrained, engineering of the era, a number of these early medium bombers found their genesis in, or were developed in parallel with, existing civilian [airliners](/Airliner) or dedicated transport aircraft. This dual-purpose design philosophy allowed for economies of scale and expedited development, though it occasionally led to compromises in optimal combat performance. Notable examples of this trend include the formidable [Heinkel He 111](/Heinkel_He_111), with its distinctive glazed nose, which would become a ubiquitous symbol of the early [Luftwaffe](/Luftwaffe) bombing campaigns; the [Junkers Ju 86](/Junkers_Ju_86), another German design initially conceived for both military and civilian roles; the elegant Italian [Savoia-Marchetti SM.79](/Savoia-Marchetti_SM.79), often referred to as the "Sparrowhawk"; the American [Douglas B-18](/Douglas_B-18_Bolo), which shared significant lineage with the DC-2 airliner; and the British [Armstrong Whitworth Whitley](/Armstrong_Whitworth_Whitley), a robust, if somewhat ungainly, heavy night bomber that served extensively in the early stages of the conflict.

As the world plunged headlong into [World War II](/World_War_II), the definition of a medium bomber crystallized, at least for a time, into a generally accepted set of parameters. A [level bomber](/High_level_bombing) of this class was typically expected to deliver approximately 4,000 pounds (1,800 kg) of [ordnance](/Aircraft_ordnance) over operational [ranges](/Range_(aeronautics)) extending from about 1,500 to 2,000 miles (2,400 to 3,200 km). For comparison, the much-vaunted [heavy bombers](/Heavy_bomber) were generally those capable of carrying a nominal load of 8,000 pounds (3,600 kg) or more, a capacity that would grow exponentially as the war progressed. Conversely, the lighter end of the spectrum, the [light bombers](/Light_bomber), typically managed a payload of up to 2,000 lb (907 kg). While these distinctions provided a useful framework for military planners and strategists, they were, like many human attempts at rigid categorization, destined to become blurred and eventually obsolete. The rapid pace of wartime innovation meant that what was "medium" one year could be "light" the next, and what seemed "heavy" could soon be dwarfed by new behemoths of the sky.

Indeed, these carefully drawn distinctions began to dissolve with alarming speed by the midpoint of [World War II](/World_War_II). The relentless march of technological progress meant that the average [fighter aircraft](/Fighter_aircraft), once solely focused on air-to-air combat, could now itself carry a substantial 2,000 lb (907 kg) [bombload](/Aerial_bomb), encroaching directly upon the traditional domain of the light bomber. This blurring of roles was further accelerated by dramatic advances in [powerplants](/Aircraft_engine) and fundamental [aerospace engineering](/Aerospace_engineering) principles. The cumulative effect was a paradigm shift that allowed [light bombers](/Light_bomber), specialized [tactical bombers](/Tactical_bombing), and, most significantly, the advent of [jet](/Jet_aircraft) [fighter-bombers](/Fighter-bomber) to effectively subsume and surpass the roles previously performed by the dedicated medium bomber class. The single-purpose aircraft, in many ways, was giving way to the multi-role combat machine, a trend that continues to this day.

Following the devastating conclusion of [World War II](/World_War_II), the term "medium bomber" largely faded from common usage within military aviation circles. This disappearance can be attributed to several converging factors. Firstly, the massive demobilization efforts undertaken by the victorious [air forces](/Air_force) meant a significant culling of existing equipment. Secondly, and perhaps more importantly, many of the most heavily produced medium bomber types of the war had, within a shockingly short span of time, become technologically obsolescent, outpaced by the very advancements they helped to inspire. While numerous subsequent [aircraft](/Fixed-wing_aircraft) were undoubtedly designed with performance characteristics and load-carrying capacities that would have once placed them squarely in the "medium bomber" [range](/Range_(aeronautics)), they were instead rebranded and referred to as [tactical bombers](/Tactical_bombing) or dedicated [strike aircraft](/Attack_aircraft). This linguistic shift reflected a new strategic reality. Illustrative examples of these post-war descendants include the iconic British [English Electric Canberra](/English_Electric_Canberra), a remarkably versatile and high-performance jet bomber introduced in the 1950s, along with its American license-built counterpart, the [Martin B-57](/Martin_B-57_Canberra). Similarly, the [Soviet](/Soviet_Union) [Ilyushin Il-28](/Ilyushin_Il-28), known by the NATO reporting name "Beagle," emerged as a highly successful and widely exported jet bomber fulfilling a comparable role.

Interestingly, a brief, if somewhat semantically muddled, resurgence of the term occurred within the U.S. [Strategic Air Command](/Strategic_Air_Command) (SAC) during the 1950s. SAC employed the classification "medium bomber" to differentiate its then-new [Boeing B-47 Stratojets](/Boeing_B-47_Stratojet) from the significantly larger, intercontinental-range [Boeing B-52 Stratofortress](/Boeing_B-52_Stratofortress), which were designated "heavy bombers" within their bombardment wings. Furthermore, older, piston-engined [B-29](/Boeing_B-29_Superfortress) and [B-50](/Boeing_B-50_Superfortress) heavy bombers were also retrospectively redesignated as "medium" during this period. However, this [nomenclature](/Nomenclature) was purely a bureaucratic and semantic exercise, bearing little resemblance to the original [World War II](/World_War_II) definitions. Both the B-47 and B-52 were advanced [strategic bombers](/Strategic_bomber) that dwarfed their wartime predecessors in sheer size, performance, and load-carrying capability, rendering the "medium" label almost comically inappropriate in a historical context. In a similar vein, the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force) occasionally referred to its formidable [V bomber](/V_bomber) force—comprising the Vickers Valiant, Avro Vulcan, and Handley Page Victor—as "medium bombers," but this was primarily a distinction based on their operational [range](/Range_(aeronautics)) rather than their immense payload capacity, which far exceeded any wartime "heavy."

Despite the official abandonment of the term, the underlying *mission* of the "medium bomber" has, in essence, persisted. The development of [aircraft](/Fixed-wing_aircraft) that fulfill this strategic niche, though under different names, has continued unabated. These highly capable machines have been extensively employed in numerous post-[World War II](/World_War_II) conflicts, demonstrating the enduring utility of a platform capable of delivering substantial firepower over considerable distances without necessarily possessing the intercontinental reach of a full-fledged strategic bomber. Contemporary examples of these "mediums in all but name" include dedicated [tactical bombers](/Tactical_bombing) such as the Soviet/Russian [Sukhoi Su-24](/Sukhoi_Su-24) "Fencer" and its more modern derivative, the [Su-34](/Sukhoi_Su-34) "Fullback"; the iconic American [General Dynamics F-111](/General_Dynamics_F-111_Aardvark) "Aardvark," renowned for its variable-sweep wings and precision strike capabilities; the Chinese [Shenyang J-16](/Shenyang_J-16), a multi-role fighter-bomber; and the versatile [McDonnell Douglas F-15E](/McDonnell_Douglas_F-15E_Strike_Eagle) "Strike Eagle." These aircraft consistently boast a significantly greater [payload](/Payload) capacity and operational [range](/Range_(aeronautics)) than typical [fighter-bombers](/Fighter-bomber), yet they remain distinct from the truly gargantuan strategic bombers that represent the apex of aerial ordnance delivery.

## Medium bombers

### Introduced prior to World War II (September 1, 1939)

*   [**Armstrong Whitworth Whitley**](/Armstrong_Whitworth_Whitley) — The first of three British medium bombers to enter service, the Whitley was a twin-engine aircraft characterized by its distinctive nose-down stance on the ground and its robust, if slow, performance in the early war years. It served extensively as a night bomber before being relegated to reconnaissance and transport roles.
*   [**Bloch MB.210**](/Bloch_MB.210) — A French twin-engine monoplane, the MB.210 was already considered somewhat obsolete by the outbreak of World War II, suffering from poor defensive armament and insufficient speed, though it represented an early attempt at modernizing the French bomber fleet.
*   [**CANT Z.1007**](/CANT_Z.1007) — An elegant Italian three-engined medium bomber, the "Alcione" (Kingfisher) was primarily constructed of wood, giving it a distinctive appearance. It saw service in various theaters, including the Battle of Britain and the Eastern Front.
*   [**Douglas B-18 Bolo**](/Douglas_B-18_Bolo) — This American twin-engine medium bomber was directly developed from the highly successful DC-2 airliner design, highlighting the commonality between civilian and military aviation in the 1930s. It was largely replaced by more modern types like the B-17 before the US entered World War II.
*   [**Douglas B-23 Dragon**](/Douglas_B-23_Dragon) — An improved version of the B-18 Bolo, the B-23 featured a more streamlined fuselage, more powerful engines, and a tail gunner's position, but only a limited number were produced before more advanced designs superseded it.
*   [**Dornier Do 23**](/Dornier_Do_23) — A German twin-engine bomber of conventional design, the Do 23 was an early precursor to the more famous Do 17 and He 111, seeing limited service before the outbreak of hostilities.
*   [**Fiat BR.20 Cicogna**](/Fiat_BR.20_Cicogna) — This twin-engine Italian bomber was notable as the first all-metal Italian bomber, representing a significant step forward for the Regia Aeronautica. It saw action in the Spanish Civil War and the early stages of World War II, including limited deployments to the Battle of Britain.
*   [**Fokker T.V**](/Fokker_T.V) — A twin-engine medium bomber designed for the Dutch army air force ( _Luchtvaartafdeling_ ), the T.V was a relatively modern design for its time, intended to act as a "flying cruiser" capable of both bombing and air defense. It saw brief, but intense, combat during the German invasion of the Netherlands in May 1940.
*   [**Handley Page Hampden**](/Handley_Page_Hampden) — A distinctive British medium bomber, often dubbed the "Flying Panhandle" due to its narrow fuselage, the Hampden was almost as fast as the [Bristol Blenheim](/Bristol_Blenheim) light bomber. It served with distinction in the early night bombing campaigns over Germany.
*   [**Heinkel He 111**](/Heinkel_He_111) — An iconic German twin-engine bomber, the He 111, with its distinctive glazed "greenhouse" nose on later variants, was a cornerstone of the [Luftwaffe](/Luftwaffe)'s bomber force throughout the war. While often considered a medium bomber, the [Luftwaffe](/Luftwaffe) sometimes classified it as a heavy bomber for specific long-range or heavy payload missions.
*   [**Ilyushin DB-3**](/Ilyushin_DB-3) — This Soviet twin-engine long-range bomber was a crucial precursor to the more widely produced and famous [Il-4](/Ilyushin_Il-4). It was instrumental in early Soviet long-range bombing operations, including raids on Berlin in 1941.
*   [**Junkers Ju 52**](/Junkers_Ju_52) — Primarily known as a transport aircraft, the venerable "Tante Ju" (Aunt Ju) was briefly pressed into service as a rudimentary bomber during the [Spanish Civil War](/Spanish_Civil_War) by the Condor Legion, a role it quickly shed for its more suitable transport duties.
*   [**Junkers Ju 86**](/Junkers_Ju_86) — A German twin-engine aircraft that saw limited success as a bomber, the Ju 86 was developed in parallel with the He 111. It notably saw service as a high-altitude reconnaissance aircraft during the war, utilizing its diesel engines for extended range.
*   [**Lioré et Olivier LeO 45**](/Lior%C3%A9_et_Olivier_LeO_45) — This fast French medium bomber was one of the most modern aircraft in the French Air Force at the outbreak of World War II, boasting impressive speed and a relatively heavy bombload. Despite its capabilities, it could not stem the tide of the German invasion.
*   [**Martin B-10**](/Martin_B-10) — An American twin-engine monoplane, the B-10 was remarkably advanced at the time of its 1934 service introduction, setting new standards for bomber speed and performance and winning the Collier Trophy. It was a significant design leap for the USAAC.
*   [**Mitsubishi G3M**](/Mitsubishi_G3M) — Known to the [Allies](/Allies_of_World_War_II) as "Nell," this Japanese twin-engine land-based naval bomber was instrumental in the early stages of the Pacific War, particularly in sinking HMS _Prince of Wales_ and HMS _Repulse_. It possessed exceptional range for its time.
*   [**Mitsubishi Ki-21**](/Mitsubishi_Ki-21) — Designated "Sally" by the Allies, this Japanese twin-engine bomber was a workhorse for the [Imperial Japanese Army Air Service](/Imperial_Japanese_Army_Air_Service), replacing some of the older Fiat BR.20 bombers acquired from Italy. It saw extensive service in China and Southeast Asia.
*   [**PZL.37 Łoś**](/PZL.37_%C5%81o%C5%9B) — The "Elk" was perhaps the most advanced Polish aircraft at the time of the German invasion of Poland in 1939, a sleek twin-engine medium bomber that was fast and capable, though too few were available to make a significant impact.
*   [**Savoia-Marchetti SM.79**](/Savoia-Marchetti_SM.79) — This distinctive [three-engined](/Trimotor) Italian medium bomber, known as the "Sparrowhawk," was highly successful, particularly when adapted for use as a torpedo bomber early in [World War II](/World_War_II) in the Mediterranean theater, earning a fearsome reputation against Allied shipping.
*   [**Vickers Wellington**](/Vickers_Wellington) — The most-produced British medium bomber of the war, the "Wimpy" was renowned for its unique geodetic aluminum lattice airframe, a revolutionary design by [Barnes Wallis](/Barnes_Wallis) that offered exceptional strength and damage resistance. It was capable of a remarkable 2,500 miles [range](/Range_(aeronautics)) on certain missions and was a mainstay of Bomber Command in the early war.

### World War II

*   [**de Havilland Mosquito**](/De_Havilland_Mosquito) — The "Wooden Wonder" was an extraordinary British twin-engine aircraft, primarily constructed from wood, making it incredibly fast and difficult to detect by radar. It was considered a highly versatile multi-role aircraft, excelling as a bomber, fighter, and reconnaissance platform, often outrunning contemporary enemy fighters.
*   [**Dornier Do 217**](/Dornier_Do_217) — A powerful German twin-engine bomber, the Do 217 was a larger and more capable evolution of the Do 17. It was considered a heavy bomber by the [Luftwaffe](/Luftwaffe) for certain specialized missions, capable of carrying a significant bombload and equipped with potent defensive armament. It also saw use as a maritime patrol aircraft and night fighter.
*   [**Ilyushin Il-4**](/Ilyushin_Il-4) — A robust and reliable Soviet twin-engine bomber, the Il-4 was an evolution of the DB-3 and served as the backbone of Soviet long-range bomber aviation throughout the war, participating in numerous critical campaigns from the Eastern Front to the Pacific.
*   [**Junkers Ju 88**](/Junkers_Ju_88) — One of the most versatile aircraft of [World War II](/World_War_II), this German twin-engine machine excelled in an astonishing array of roles, including level bomber, dive bomber, torpedo bomber, night fighter, and reconnaissance aircraft, a true jack-of-all-trades that served on every front.
*   [**Martin B-26 Marauder**](/Martin_B-26_Marauder) — This American twin-engine medium bomber initially earned a dubious reputation for its high accident rate during training, leading to the nickname "Widowmaker." However, once properly mastered, it achieved the lowest mission loss rate of any [USAAF](/United_States_Army_Air_Forces) bomber in [World War II](/World_War_II), proving to be a highly effective and survivable combat aircraft.
*   [**Mitsubishi G4M**](/Mitsubishi_G4M) — Known to the [Allies](/Allies_of_World_War_II) as "Betty," this Japanese twin-engine land-based naval bomber was infamous for its long range but also its vulnerability due to a lack of self-sealing fuel tanks, earning it the grim nickname "the flying Zippo." It was involved in many critical actions, including the attack on Pearl Harbor and the sinking of the HMS _Prince of Wales_ and HMS _Repulse_.
*   [**Mitsubishi Ki-67 Hiryū**](/Mitsubishi_Ki-67) — Allied reporting name "Peggy," this Japanese twin-engine heavy bomber was considered a heavy bomber by the [Imperial Japanese Army Air Service](/Imperial_Japanese_Army_Air_Service). It was a well-designed aircraft with good speed, range, and defensive armament, though it arrived too late and in too few numbers to significantly alter the course of the war.
*   [**Nakajima Ki-49 Donryu**](/Nakajima_Ki-49) — Allied reporting name "Helen," this Japanese twin-engine bomber was designed to replace the Ki-21 but proved to be largely unsuccessful due to its inadequate speed and defensive armament against newer Allied fighters, suffering heavy losses.
*   [**North American B-25 Mitchell**](/North_American_B-25_Mitchell) — One of the most famous American medium bombers, the B-25 was the most-produced American medium bomber of [World War II](/World_War_II). It gained legendary status for the Doolittle Raid on Tokyo in 1942 and served in all theaters, performing a wide variety of missions, including ground attack with up to fourteen forward-firing .50 caliber machine guns.
*   [**Savoia-Marchetti SM.84**](/Savoia-Marchetti_SM.84) — Intended as a replacement for the highly successful SM.79, this Italian three-engined bomber proved to be less effective in service. Its performance was generally inferior to its predecessor, leading to the SM.79 remaining in service even after the SM.84's introduction.
*   [**Tupolev Tu-2**](/Tupolev_Tu-2) — A highly effective Soviet twin-engine medium bomber, the Tu-2 was known for its robust construction, good speed, and heavy bombload. It was used in multiple roles similar to the German Junkers Ju 88, including dive bombing and reconnaissance, and proved to be one of the best bombers of the Eastern Front.
*   [**Yermolayev Yer-2**](/Yermolayev_Yer-2) — This Soviet twin-engine medium bomber was developed from the failed Bartini Stal-7 transport aircraft. It saw service both as a long-range bomber and as a heavy ground attacker, though its use in the latter role often resulted in heavy losses due to inadequate defensive capabilities against determined fighter opposition.
*   [**Yokosuka P1Y Ginga**](/Yokosuka_P1Y) — Designated "Frances" by the Allies, this Japanese twin-engine medium bomber was developed for the [Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service](/Imperial_Japanese_Navy_Air_Service). While classified as a medium by the Japanese, its size, weight, and speed characteristics were often more akin to Allied light bombers or attack aircraft such as the [Douglas A-26 Invader](/Douglas_A-26_Invader).

### Post World War II

*   [**English Electric Canberra**](/English_Electric_Canberra) — A groundbreaking British jet bomber introduced in the 1950s, the Canberra was renowned for its high altitude and speed capabilities, making it notoriously difficult to intercept in its early service years. It proved to be a remarkably adaptable design, serving in numerous roles and with many air forces worldwide.
*   [**Ilyushin Il-28**](/Ilyushin_Il-28) — Known by the NATO reporting name "Beagle," this [Soviet](/Soviet_Union) jet bomber was the primary tactical bomber of the Soviet Air Force and widely exported to Warsaw Pact nations and other allies. It was a rugged and reliable aircraft, roughly analogous to the Canberra in its capabilities and role.
*   [**Martin B-57 Canberra**](/Martin_B-57_Canberra) — This was the U.S. license-built development of the English Electric Canberra, adapted and produced by the Glenn L. Martin Company. The B-57 saw extensive combat service, particularly during the Vietnam War, performing tactical bombing, reconnaissance, and electronic warfare missions.
*   [**Douglas A-3 Skywarrior**](/Douglas_A-3_Skywarrior) — Affectionately known as "The Whale," this U.S. [naval](/Carrier-based_aircraft) jet [strike aircraft](/Attack_aircraft) was the largest and heaviest aircraft ever to operate from an aircraft carrier. A derivative was also adopted by the United States Air Force [Tactical Air Command](/Tactical_Air_Command) and designated as the [B-66](/Douglas_B-66_Destroyer) "tactical light bomber," despite its considerable size and payload.
*   [**North American AJ Savage**](/North_American_AJ_Savage) — A unique U.S. [naval](/Carrier-based_aircraft) medium bomber designed for carrier operations, the Savage was powered by an unusual combination of two piston engines and a single turbojet engine buried in the rear fuselage, allowing for enhanced performance during critical phases of flight. It was initially intended as a nuclear strike aircraft.
*   [**North American A-5 Vigilante**](/North_American_A-5_Vigilante) — A sleek and powerful U.S. naval [supersonic](/Supersonic) jet [strike aircraft](/Attack_aircraft), the Vigilante was originally designed as a nuclear bomber but was later converted to a high-speed reconnaissance platform, excelling in demanding intelligence-gathering missions.
*   [**Dassault Mirage IV**](/Dassault_Mirage_IV) — This elegant [French](/France) supersonic jet [strategic bomber](/Strategic_bomber) formed the core of France's nuclear deterrent force, the _Force de Frappe_, for decades. While designated strategic, its range and payload characteristics often placed it in a similar operational bracket to the larger "medium" concepts of other nations.
*   [**Grumman A-6 Intruder**](/Grumman_A-6_Intruder) — A rugged and reliable U.S. [naval](/Carrier-based_aircraft) strike aircraft, the A-6 Intruder was approximate in physical size to a [World War II](/World_War_II) medium bomber. However, its impressive range and payload capabilities, particularly its ability to deliver precision ordnance in all weather conditions, were comparable to a [World War II heavy bomber](/Heavy_bomber).
*   [**Blackburn Buccaneer**](/Blackburn_Buccaneer) — A potent [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) carrier-based maritime strike aircraft, the Buccaneer was designed for low-level, high-speed penetration missions against naval targets. Its robust construction and formidable payload made it a highly effective attack platform, later serving with the Royal Air Force.
*   [**General Dynamics F-111**](/General_Dynamics_F-111_Aardvark) — An iconic U.S. supersonic [swing-wing](/Variable-sweep_wing) strike aircraft, the F-111 "Aardvark" was revolutionary for its variable-geometry wings, allowing it to excel in both high-speed, low-altitude penetration and long-range missions. It redefined the concept of the tactical bomber with its precision strike capabilities.
*   [**Sukhoi Su-24**](/Sukhoi_Su-24) — A formidable [Soviet](/Soviet_Union) supersonic swing-wing strike aircraft, the Su-24 "Fencer" was remarkably similar in role and configuration to the American F-111. It was designed for all-weather, day/night attack missions, carrying a heavy ordnance load and employing advanced avionics for its time.

